{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation* (Vols. II and IV)** directly engages this question in discussions of authority structures among enslaved or subjugated peoples.[^1][^2]\n\nIn Vol. II, Ch. 19, describing Malay societies, Comte notes that a chief can be deposed or killed by higher chiefs if guilty toward them, showing conditional authority limits even in hierarchical systems.[^3]\n\nIn Vol. IV, Ch. 23, he contrasts doctrines where a sultan \"cannot be deposed... whatever crimes he may have committed against his people\" (per Muslim priests), but can be if he violates church laws, highlighting theological limits on royal power versus popular deposition.[^4]\n\nNo other works in the corpus address kingly deposition or authority limits substantively; poetry mentions \"tyrants\" metaphorically, but lacks political analysis. The 37 works focus more on property, economy, poetry, and Indic law than monarchical resistance.\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/translation/].\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/23-de-l-inegalite-des-fortunes-produite-par-l-esclava/translation/].\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, Ch. 19, [p-4039fe](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/19-des-rapports-observes-entre-les-moyens-d-existence/translation/#p-4039fe).\n\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, Ch. 23, [p-98e169](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/23-de-l-inegalite-des-fortunes-produite-par-l-esclava/translation/#p-98e169).",
